South America
---
Brazil update. 30 Mar 2016. (reported) The Ministry of Health continues to investigate 4291 suspected cases of microcephaly or other central nervous system [CNS] alterations suggestive of congenital infection. Of the concluded cases, 944 were confirmed, and 1541 were discarded. Since the beginning of the investigation in 2015, 6776 suspected microcephaly cases were reported.

Of the total confirmed microcephaly cases, 130 were laboratory positive for Zika [virus]. However, the Ministry of Health reiterated that this number is not an adequate representative of the total number of cases related to the virus.

This week [up to 30 Mar 2016], the states of Acre, Amapa, Santa Catarina and Rio Grande do Sul reported local circulation of Zika virus to the Ministry of Health. Currently, all 27 units of the Federation [states and the federal district] have Zika virus circulating.

The 944 confirmed cases occur in 358 municipalities in 21 units of the Federation: Alagoas, Bahia, Ceara, Maranhao, Paraiba, Pernambuco, Piaua, Rio Grande do Norte, Sergipe, Espirito Santo, Minas Gerais, Rio de Janeiro, Amazonas, Para, Rondania, Distrito Federal, Goias, Mato Grosso, Mato Grosso do Sul, Rio Grande do Sul and Parana.

The 1541 discarded cases were classified as normal presentations or presented with microcephaly or abnormal CNS alterations due to non-infectious causes.

As of 26 Mar [2016], 208 deaths (fetal or neonatal) suspected of having microcephaly or CNS alterations after birth or during gestation (aborted of stillbirth) were registered. Of these, 47 were confirmed with microcephaly or CNS alterations. An additional 139 continue under investigation, and 22 were discarded.

The 6776 reported cases are found in 1265 municipalities in every region in the country. The majority (5315 cases, 78 percent) are in the northeast region. Pernambuco is the unit [state] with the greatest number of cases which are still under investigation (1207 cases), followed by Bahia (676), Paraiba (412), Rio de Janeiro (322), Rio Grande do Norte (289) and Ceara (240).

It is worth clarifying that the Ministry of Health is investigating all the cases of microcephaly and other CNS alterations reported by the states for the possible relation with Zika virus and other congenital infections. Microcephaly could be caused by various infectious agents besides Zika [virus], such as syphilis, toxoplasmosis, other infectious agents, rubeola, cytomegalovirus and herpes virus.
http://portalsaude.saude.gov.br/index.php/o-ministerio/principal/secretarias/svs/noticias-svs/22874-microcefalia-ministerio-da-saude-investiga-4-291-casos-suspeitos-no-pais [in Portuguese]

Colombia. 27 Mar 2016. (susp.) Since the beginning of the outbreak, 56 477 (conf.) cases, of whom 10 812 are pregnant women with 997 infected with Zika virus. Babies with congenital malformations: 50 as of 19 Mar 2016; Guillain-Barre syndrome: 258 cases [no mention if they had been infected with Zika virus]; Departments with active Zika virus transmission: Meta, Quindao, Valle del Cauca.
http://pe.globedia.com/colombia-registra-838-casos-zika-812-embarazadas?utm_source=Bolet%C3%ADn%20de%20noticias&utm_medium=link&utm_campaign=Bolet%C3%ADn [in Spanish]

